Architecture plan for issues #71-#73

Repository shape
- Frontend: React + TypeScript + Vite under src/.
- Desktop shell/backend: Tauri 2 Rust app under src-tauri/; no backend changes are needed for these UI-only issues.
- Global app chrome styling is centralized in src/styles.css.
- CodeMirror setup and editor chrome theme live in src/components/editor/CodeMirrorEditor.tsx.
- LaTeX token highlighting lives in src/editor/latexHighlighting.ts.

Module structure, file organization, shared types
- Keep the theme implementation CSS-first: introduce Darcula design tokens in :root in src/styles.css and migrate existing selectors to consume those tokens.
- Do not add a theme state/store for this batch; the issues request a cohesive dark mode rather than runtime light/dark switching.
- Treat the CSS token names from issue #71 as the shared theme contract for app chrome:
  --bg-main, --bg-shell, --bg-panel, --bg-panel-alt, --bg-hover, --bg-editor,
  --border, --border-soft, --text-main, --text-strong, --text-muted,
  --accent, --accent-hover, --selection, --success, --warning, --danger.
- Keep editor-specific CodeMirror colors in CodeMirrorEditor.tsx for now because issue #72 names exact CodeMirror target colors and that theme is defined in TypeScript, not CSS.
- Keep syntax-specific colors in latexHighlighting.ts because they map directly to @lezer/highlight tags.
- No new dependencies are required.

Issue dependencies and sequencing
1. #71 should land first. It establishes the Darcula tokens and converts the workspace shell, panes, headers, controls, file tree, template manager, compile log, preview, status badges, errors, shadows, hover states, and scrollbars away from the current hardcoded light palette.
2. #72 depends visually on #71. It updates the CodeMirror editor surface to match the dark app chrome while preserving existing editor extensions and behaviors.
3. #73 depends visually on #72. It recolors LaTeX syntax tags so source text is readable and stylistically consistent on the #2b2b2b editor background.

Key design decisions
- Use the exact palette from issue #71 for app chrome and state colors.
- Set color-scheme: dark in :root so native controls match the dark UI.
- Prefer Inter/system sans for UI chrome and JetBrains Mono/system monospace for editor/compile-log text.
- Preserve current layout behavior and component structure; this is a visual/theme migration only.
- Use compact IDE-like header spacing while keeping existing minimum pane/layout constraints.
- Use subtle Darcula hover/focus treatments: hover background --bg-hover and accent borders instead of bright light outlines.
- Ensure all previously white/light surfaces are migrated, including popovers, inputs, empty states, diagnostics, raw logs, preview background, PDF canvas borders/shadows, and disabled states.
- Keep semantic status colors tokenized: success uses --success, warnings use --warning, failures/errors use --danger.
- Avoid scattering new literals in src/styles.css except where issue #71 explicitly requests scrollbar colors or unavoidable derived values; prefer CSS variables for maintainability.

Validation plan
- Run npm run build after each issue or after the full visual batch to validate TypeScript and Vite bundling.
- Run npm run test:frontend to ensure existing editor/snippet/error tests still pass.
- Manually inspect the app in dev/preview if possible to verify there are no leftover light backgrounds or low-contrast text.
